  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights at an airport can seem daunting, but with some preparation, it can be a smooth process. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you navigate your flight change in Paris:\n\n1. **Check Your Itinerary**: Review your flight details before you travel. Make sure you know the arrival and departure times, as well as the terminal information for both flights.\n\n2. **Arrival in Paris**:\n   - **Follow Signs**: Upon arrival at Paris, follow the signs to the connecting flights or transit area.\n   - **Passport Control**: Depending on your arrival and departure terminals, you might have to go through passport control. If you're traveling within the Schengen Zone, you might not need to go through passport control again.\n\n3. **Find Your Departure Terminal**:\n   - **Check Your Boarding Pass**: Look for your departure terminal and gate information on your boarding pass.\n   - **Airport Maps**: Paris Charles de Gaulle (CDG) and Paris Orly (ORY) are the main airports. If you are at CDG, it's a large airport with multiple terminals. Use airport maps and information screens to navigate to your next terminal.\n\n4. **Security Check**: If you are changing terminals, you may need to go through security again. Ensure you have all your liquids and electronics ready for inspection.\n\n5. **Transfer Between Terminals**:\n   - **CDG**: If you need to transfer between terminals at CDG, you can use the free shuttle bus service (N2) or the CDGVAL light rail system.\n   - **ORY**: At Orly, there are shuttle buses that connect the South and West terminals.\n\n6. **Relax and Wait**: Once you reach your departure gate, take a moment to relax. Keep an eye on the departure boards for any updates or gate changes.\n\n7. **Boarding**: Be at your gate ahead of the boarding time indicated on your boarding pass. Boarding usually starts about 30-45 minutes before the flight departure time.\n\nAdditional Tips:\n- **Luggage**: If your luggage is checked through to Prague, you won't need to collect it in Paris. If not, make sure you retrieve it and re-check it for your next flight.\n- **Time Management**: Allow ample time for your transfer. Airports recommend arriving at least 2 hours before your flight for international departures.\n- **Language**: Paris airports have multilingual signs, and staff generally speak English, so don't hesitate to ask for help if needed.\n\nSafe travels and enjoy your trip to Prague!",
